{"annotations": [{"id": ["mesh:D010100"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "oxygen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995973706245422, "span": {"begin": 8, "end": 14}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010100"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "oxygen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996950626373291, "span": {"begin": 78, "end": 84}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1536"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NOX2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9797700643539429, "span": {"begin": 331, "end": 335}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:57783"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NADPH", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9986977577209473, "span": {"begin": 339, "end": 344}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:27035"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NADPH oxidase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9422178864479065, "span": {"begin": 339, "end": 352}}, {"id": ["CL:0000235"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "macrophage", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8797237873077393, "span": {"begin": 357, "end": 367}}, {"id": ["mesh:D028361"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "mitochondrial dysfunction", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9908655881881714, "span": {"begin": 492, "end": 517}}, {"id": ["mesh:D001778"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "coagulopathy", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999797344207764, "span": {"begin": 533, "end": 545}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Polymorphonuclear leucocytes", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8436450958251953, "span": {"begin": 618, "end": 646}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "neutrophils", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.745299756526947, "span": {"begin": 672, "end": 683}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:57783"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NADPH", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994198083877563, "span": {"begin": 723, "end": 728}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:27035"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NADPH oxidase complex", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9684533476829529, "span": {"begin": 723, "end": 744}}], "text": "ROS are oxygen-derived molecules that oxidize molecules or are converted into oxygen radicals (Andr&eacute;-L&eacute;vigne D, et al., 2017). ROS have dual-effects which are cell damaging or beneficial roles (Andr&eacute;-L&eacute;vigne D, et al., 2017, Beckman KB and Ames BN, 1998, Bedard K and KH Krause, 2007). ROS generated by NOX2, a NADPH oxidase, in macrophage play an important role in killing of phagocytosed microorganisms (Bedard K and KH Krause, 2007). The ROS accumulation cause mitochondrial dysfunction which leads to coagulopathy associated with inflammatory signaling pathways (Saleh J et al., 2020). Polymorphonuclear leucocytes, commonly referred to as neutrophils, generate large amounts of ROS via the NADPH oxidase complex (Barrett CD et al., 2018).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:32:01 +0000 2026"}